This has been designed to house a Raspberry Pi Zero and Pi camera all in one package. No supports are required if you orientate everything correctly.

  1. The camhinge is a push fit into the campicase and my tolerances were such that I didn't need to glue it.
  2. The Pi camera is installed in the camcase and the camcaselid clips on the back securing it.
  3. The Pi camera cable (for the Zero) passes though the camhinge into the campicase and is inserted into the Pi Zero slot.
  4. The camcase is secured to the camhinge using a M3 25mm bolt and nut.
  5. The Pi Zero is secured into the case with M2.5 5mm screws.
  6. The campicaselid clips on to the campicase.

I set up my Pi with Raspbian and Motion Eye to provide streaming. These are the steps I took to get Motion Eye running on the zero:

http://snardfarkle.blogspot.com.au/2016/04/ip-camera-on-raspberry-pi-3-using.html

This results in a fully configurable security camera with motion detection, local/remote storage of images captured, email notifications of movement etc.

description.text:
Recently I was gifted a Gerber STL 2.5 Drop Point Fine edge knife.
This blade was so insanely handy for stripping coax, I just had to take it to work with me (which is pretty much everywhere)

So I made a magnetically retained holster for it.

Best suited for 30-35mm wide belts.

I suggest you print it vertically (as shown) with support columns.
If printing in ABS, an acetone dip is highly recommended for strength.

You will also need a 10mm diameter, 1.75mm neodymium magnet.
This should stay in the slot just from the tight tolerance alone, but if not, use a touch of superglue.

The thumb slot is modeled on my rather sizable thumbs, if you want to remix this, let me know and I'll post source files.

Yet another extended puzzle from Bill Cutler. This is definitive one of the hardest puzzle, ten steps needed to remove the first one!

This STL models have 0,4mm tolerance, so it works also fine with filament which extends a lot, but it is a bit loose on the other side.

However you can generate your own STL files with your own sizes and tolerances easily. Just download the FreeCAD v0.17 construction file and edit the two parameters in the spreadsheet.

A solution for the burr is available on youtube: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YgzFlt1aAug

title: Cat Litter Scoop for Biokats Micro-Fresh

description.text:
Yes, I know, "Just another cat litter scoop!". But for my brand of cat litter (Biokats Micro-Fresh) I need a shovel with a mesh size of 4mm as the best compromise between catching the finest clots and wasting unused cat litter. And because my maine coons produce big, big lumps in their XXL-toilet I need a big and stable scoop.
But there were no suitable shovels to buy or to print. So I made my own one.
It's not streamlined or artificial designed but it works very well for me and does it's job.
For a convenient angle of the handle and to prevent a lot of support structures the handle will be printed separated from the blade and attached after print. Additionally the handle will become more stable if the layers are running in parallel with the shape.
To save filament the handle is designed hollow but is stable enough for the biggest lumps.

Edit 2017/07/22: Added a bigger model of the shovel blade to sieve more effective in an XXL-toilet.

Edit 2017/08/07: V2 of blades with strengthened leading edge and smoother transition from handle to blade uploaded

Use concentric external infill for better stability.
I recommend to print the blade with polypropylene. It's nearly unbreakable and easy to clean because of its dirt rejecting surface. If printing with PP use mouse ears at the blades corners to hold them down on the print bed (see last picture).

There is no glue necessary for mounting. The holder fits tight into the reception on the blade.
In some cases it will need some careful hits to drive the handle into the reception.

This is my version of the popular back covers for a Nema 23 stepper motor. I used a grabcad file and modified it to include the bolt holes and also added the cable guard for a dual shaft stepper motor.   
I have included the files for right and left side exit for the wires and one to have a plug out of both sides for series connections (like two motors that run on the same driver as in some cnc routers).
THESE ARE FOR THE ACTUAL NEMA 23 MOTORS!!  
They will NOT work for the 60mm "nema 23" steppers.  
It is designed to work with the GX16 connectors commonly used with hobby CNC machines.
Thanks for the correction on connection type from AlexWYYC, it is not "XLR connectors" although some sellers on ebay refer to them as such.

These connectors can be found on ebay by searching "GX16-4" if you search a little while you can usually find 10 of these for around 10 bucks.
You will need to purchase 4 M3x25mm machine screws from your local hardware store. In most cases there is not enough thread depth in the motor screw holes left for the mounting screws, so the motor screws need to be shortened. To do this, unscrew the motor screws ONE at a time (if you do all of them the motor may come apart) and file off a couple of millimeters from the screw length. A total thread depth of 3.5mm is required for`the mounting screws.  
Next, use a drill and clear the holes that were printed into the motor cover with a #16 drill bit to ensure clearance for the M3 screws. This will also give a little "wiggle room" for the screw if the tolerance is off slightly.  
These will not make a motor water tight, they are more for aesthetics but just before final assembly, placing a little bead of silicone around the edges would help keep dust and dirt out.

This gadget allows you to predetermine the movement of your unit without using rulers. Just align the center box with your unit by suspending it above your unit. Locate your unit on the board and hover the X-Wing Range Finder above the unit about 2 feet away. Looking through the center square of the X-Wing Range Finder, align the center square with your unit's base. The base should visually fill the area of the X-Wing Range Finder center square.

Press-fit the controller switch into the square hole in the "front".
Solder or connect the male pigtail to the "wall wart"

Connect all wires to the controller according to controller instructions.
Remove knob and nut from controller board and fit onto the pegs on bottom.stl
Drop middle.stl into bottom.stl

Warning: The Design in it's current state might move to much air towards the hot end, especially during the first 5mm, make sure to start the fan after the first 5mm z are printed.
A better version is in the works, without eta though.

Update: Finally got the position of the lower rear screw mount right.
Update 2.0: Added fan-bracket for top side.
Update 2.1: Added fan-bracket hinge for right side.

Mounting
  • After printing and getting rid of support materials, unscrew the screws on the front and bottom of the printhead(behind the heaterblock on the 45 degree angle part), then attach the duct to the printhead using the two screws you removed earlier.
  • Attach the blower-fan (I use a Delta 5015 compatible model) and secure it to the printhead using either tape, or the provided mounting brackets (TODO: design mounting brackets)

description.text:
This is a spring retainer for application when converting a Nerf Recon to make use of Nerf Retaliator internal components.

Due to the Recon having a greater diameter hole in the plunger spring stop, the Retaliator's spring will not rest, and passes through. This eliminates that.

Can also be used for XPT (Expanded plunger tube) Retaliators to assist in adding guidance to the plunger rod, which is nessesary due to the greater diameter plunger head yet smaller spring diameter, which if not guided, can result in misalignment of the plunger rod during firing, resulting obviously, in lesser performance.

The retainer will take up to a 12KG Turf spring (27mm compressed length, most springs are around the 21-22mm mark). The retainer can be used with the supplied 1, 2, 3mm shims to fill out the compression on any shorter compressed springs. If you print the 3 shims it will give you combinations ranging from 1-6mm, if you print two 2mm shims with the rest it will give you a combination ranging from 1-8mm!

Update: File changed to 'Open ended' version so it is compatible with stock Retaliator tube and plunger tolerances.

title: Spirit of St. Louis

description.text:
Spirit of St. Louis

Ryan NYP

Imagine sitting inside a cold, cramped, dark box for 33 and 1/2 hours without nodding off to sleep...ever! The reason for your somnambulistic-like behavior is because even the slightest attempt at sleep would result in your instant death. This instantaneous death would be caused by the explosion of 298 gallons of aviation fuel sitting at your feet and fitted to the rear bulkhead of a an active and hot rotary engine. Oh, and there's 152 gallons of Avgas in the wing over your head, too.

This was the test that Charles A. Lindbergh endured from May 21 through May 22 1927 during his recording-making non-stop solo Atlantic flight between New York (USA) and Paris (France). In recognition of his achievement, Lindbergh won the coveted Raymond Orteig prize (established in 1919) of $25,000. He also instantly became the most well-known person on the planet--a real American hero.

The bird that Lindbergh rode to his fame and fortune was a Ryan NYP monoplane named Spirit of St. Louis. It was so-named due to Lindbergh's flying for the mail service based in St. Louis, Missouri, as well as for the financial support of several St. Louis-based backers. Within a scant 60 days, at the cost of approximately $10,580, B. F. Mahoney of Ryan Airlines, Inc. in San Diego, California delivered a completed aircraft with instruments and a Wright engine.

This pioneering and heroic effort is celebrating its 90th anniversary in 2017. In honor of this celebration, this model of the Ryan NYP, Spirit of St. Louis is being provided to 3D modelers. This is a complete 1/46th scale model of the Ryan NYP aircraft along with an accurate set of decals. Assembly is straightforward; just refer to the attached photographs. You will also need plastic model cement (we recommend Testors) and masking tape for holding parts in place during the curing of the cement.

Unlike most commercial plastic models, this Spirit of St. Louis can be built in a number of different configurations: from a skeletal view to a foil-covered static display model. Use household kitchen foil and yellow glue for covering your model with this technique. Additionally, you can cover your static model with tissue paper. Use a glue stick for applying the tissue to the skeletal frame.

As a totally experimental departure from these more conventional model construction techniques, you can also try building your Spirit of St. Louis as a flying model. There is a provision for inserting a rubber motor holding post at the rear of the fuselage. You will also need to add a flying propeller to the nose of the airplane. Furthermore, use tissue for covering your experimental flying model. Tissue should only be applied to the flying surfaces (e.g., wings, elevator, and rudder) and not the fuselage. After the tissue has been applied to the flying surfaces, it must be protected with several thin coats of model airplane dope (e.g., SIG Lite-Coat).

Test glide your model prior to attempting a powered flight. The center of gravity should balance under the main spar on both wings. Don't add weight to balance the craft, rather trim plastic from either the nose or the tail until properly balanced. If you're able to make your model fly, congratulations. You are a Lucky Lindy!

This model is being provided by First in Flight Models. Along with this Ryan NYP, there are other models currently being prepared for the upcoming launch of this new modeling company.

Shop for model tissue, propellers, and rubber motors from Peck-Polymers @ peck-polymers.com
Shop for model cement from Scale Hobbyist @ scalehobbyist.com
Shop for model airplane dope from SIG Mfg Co, Inc @ sigmfg.com

description.text: We have a short, metal candle holder designed for 2-3/4" pillar candles, but the base was leaving stains on any surface on which we'd place it. I designed this holder to hold that holder - that's a lot of holding, right there! - but it will work just as well by itself without the metal insert. The inset is 99mm (3.9") in diameter and 10mm (0.39") deep. The whole thing is 110mm (4.3") tall with a base 152mm (6") in diameter. As an added bonus (for my girlfriend, anyway) if you look closely, you will see her profile imprinted on the design itself :)

Printer:

Tevo Tarantula

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

10%

I started with a profile photo of my intended target - I mean model :) - against a solid white background with her hair pulled back. This photo was then cropped in gimp with a little post-processing to cut out all traces of the background. Next, I imported the profile photo into Sketchup on a separate layer in the vertical orientation and used the [Line] and [Curves] tools to trace the profile onto another layer. I extended the top portion up a bit vertically to allow for the candle later. Working with the negative space - the area outside of her face - I drew horizontal lines from the top and bottom of the profile a distance of the radius desired for the pillar and connected those with a vertical line on the blue axis. From that vertical line, slightly below the outline, I created a circle on the horizontal plane the diameter of the intended pillar with the vertical line being the center of the circle. Selecting the circle, I used the [Follow-Me] tool on the profile outline, resulting in the a cylindrical copy of the that outline. After that, it was a simple matter of dropping the center portion to create the recess for the candle.

It's much easier to do than it is to describe, but I would be glad to help anyone interested in trying this themselves of their own loved ones.

description.text:
Today I’ve got something hot off the printer for all you iPhone 7(&6) owners out there. I’ve been working on a bumper case for my Sister's iPhone 7 and after a number of design iterations I’m now really happy with it and it’s ready to share with all of you iPhone 7 (&6) owners. I've used a minimalist look while still making it easily printable. It's designed to protrude slightly on the front and back to absorb any knocks, scratches and impacts... plus it let's your phone cool down much better than a full case will :)

I made a quick showcase video on the bumper here:-

landscape version:- https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2431698

Fitting to your phone is easy, just put the end in first and then on a flat surface push down on the top until it snaps firmly on.

Notes:

Supports are needed as this should be printed with the rear of the case facing up just as the STL file appears. The reason it's not the other way around is that the detail on the back will likely be blemished by any supports.

I now mainly use Simplyfy3D to slice for three main reasons;-

  1. the supports come away beautifully and
  2. for items that rely on tight tolerances (like this case!) it prints the most accurate that I've used and
  3. You can specify different print settings in a print so for sections with detail you can reduce layer height and for uniform sections you can increase it and get great looking prints done fast!

I suggest printing with 4 perimeters and 25% infill as there's only a handful of grams of plastic in this so don't skimp.

I suggest printing this in an improved PLA (see below) or other filament that's strong and tough.

Beware: Not all PLA's are made equal.

Most of my prototypes and a good proportion of final prints are with an 'improved' PLA from Esun called PLA Plus (sometimes called pro) and it's tough and definitely not brittle and it's really cheap too. Some other moderately priced improved PLA's I've used are Filamentum, Prusa Brand & Colorfabb Economy PLA.

I haven't tried Hatchbox, Matterhackers, Taulman InPLA and Filaform Pro PLA but I hear some good things about them.

I also use a few better quality name brand PLA's for special one off jobs like phone cases and these are quite a bit better than the Esun though up to triple the price... though bare in mind this print in the pricey filament would still only cost a couple of bucks.

For the best looking prints with a fair bit better toughness than the Esun I use either Polymaker PolyMax PLA or ColorFabb PLA PHA. If excellent toughness and strength is a priority then the Polymaker PC Max polycarbonate is the one I'll always reach for and the finish is still good too.

description.text:
This is an idea for a spice rack i had for a while.  It is a beehive construct that is design to fit 18mm X 150mm test tubes.
(It also makes a pretty nice pencil holder when you screw up and make the cells too small for the test tubes.)

• Collect the necessary parts. You will need however many test tubes (18mm x 150mm) you want, and the same number of #6 cork stoppers. (Optional: I also added labels using a label maker for ease of identification of spices.)

  • Print one cell first. It is important that you test the size of the cell on EVERY test tube as there are manufacturing deviations in their diameter that can be a problem. If the cell is too small scale it to suite.

  • Next print as many sets of three as you will need and wall support versions. (Note the wall support versions have slots in the back for mounting with screws.

  • Then fuse all the cells together using ABS glue. (Note, that you will need far more than you would for smaller projects. I recommend working in a well ventilated area and mixing glue in a polished ceramic container like a small backing ramekin.)
    • OPTIONAL: I then "polished" the exterior with a coat of acetone for sheen.

description.text:
This is yet another filament spool holder for the Wanhao D6 with bearings. This will hold standard 1KG spools and 3.5 KG spools that measure 12" x 4". The designs I tried didn't work with my cheap 608 bearings as putting pressure from only one side would lock them up. The spacer tube in the middle and the two small washers prevent this in the new design. The large tube only makes contact on the outside of the bearings so all can move smoothly. Used a 9 cm M8 screw (or 5/16, 3.5 inch), washer and nut I had around to hold this together. Use the original holder nut that came with the printer to attach.
Finally made this as I realized that all the spools I run through this where cutting into my fixed holder and particularly Ninjaflex was getting stretched quite a bit by the extruder.

description.text:
If you're like me, you have a ton of 20mm calibration cubes lying around. If you're also like me, for some reason you haven't thrown them away, despite the fact that there's almost nothing to use them for. Now you can give those cubes a purpose in life and some angular momentum with this fidget spinner.

This spinner is sized for a standard 608 skate bearing and three 20mm calibration cubes. The standard wisdom about making spinners is that you have to press the bearing in, but I've found that with the right settings you can make it tight enough to hold but loose enough that you can mash the bearing in by hand.

The tolerances in the model are exact, so you'll want to scale this up in your slicer before you print it. It worked best for me at 102% - i was able to mash the bearing in using nothing but elbow grease, and the cubes fit in tight enough that they won't fall out with normal use. Your results might vary.

I've also included two caps (which I scaled to 98% to print) - standard short caps, and tall caps that should let you set it on a table to spin.

title: PAR16 Light Fitting for GU10 LED Bulb

description.text:
A 1/4 scale replica of the ubiquitous PAR64 theatre lighting fixture. I've included cans for both a short and long version to suit your taste. For best results on the long can, line the inside surface of the tube with some aluminium foil.

UPDATE 14/07/17
Added ventilated versions of both cans to aid with heat dissipation

The print requires a couple of standard additional parts available from pretty much any hardware store:
1x GU10 ceramic base
4x 10mm M3 bolts and nuts
2x 3mm washers

The M3 bolts that secure the mount to the base also lock the tube to the base. Be sure to align the holes correctly!

Embed the 4 M3 nuts in the base, then thread the wires from the GU10 base through the other holes in the base and secure with 2 of the 10mm M3 bolts.

Fit the GU10 bulb, and slide the can of your choice over, making sure to align the holes correctly. Place the 3mm washers on the other two 10mm M3 bolts and pass them through the holes in the mount and screw them into the captive nuts on the sides of the base.

Enjoy your new light fixture :-)
